{"type":"message","id":"6b81ab2d","parentId":"58c934fe","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:07:28.905Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Clarifying Skill Locations**\n\nI realize now that my \"available skills\" list was incomplete. I was only looking at `/app/skills/`, and completely missed the skills directory at `/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/skills/`. My current thinking is focused on accurately documenting all skill locations.\n\n\n**Distinguishing Skill Categories**\n\nI'm now focusing on distinguishing between \"system\" and \"workspace\" skills. My initial \"available skills\" list, based on the provided XML, omitted workspace skills. I need to acknowledge that and explain the difference. To provide a definitive list, I'll execute `ls -F /home/node/.openclaw/workspace/skills/` to obtain a listing directly from the workspace and share that with the user.\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"<think>The user is correcting my previous statement, indicating that there *are* skills within their workspace directory (`/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/skills/`). My initial list was based on the `available_skills` block provided at boot, which typically points to system-level skills. The user's list implies there are project-specific skills in their local workspace that I didn't automatically detect through that initial mechanism.\n\nI need to confirm the contents of the `/home/node/.openclaw/workspace/skills/` directory using the `ls` command and then explain the difference between the system-wide skills and the workspace-specific ones. I'll use `ls -F` to differentiate directories from files, which is good practice for listing contents.","textSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1775218048896_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -F /home/node/.openclaw/workspace/skills/"}}],"api":"google-generative-ai","provider":"google","model":"gemini-2.5-flash","usage":{"input":21344,"output":487,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":